# Each tuple: prompt, reference answer, source IDs, required concept groups.
# A concept group uses | to separate acceptable surface forms for deterministic audit scoring.
LEVELS: dict[int, dict] = {}

LEVELS[1] = {
    "id": "L1_foundations", "category": "Biomedical and bioinformatics foundations",
    "dimensions": ["biomedical_knowledge", "bioinformatics_fundamentals", "uncertainty_calibration"],
    "items": [
        ("A FASTQ file arrives from a sequencer. Explain what each four-line record contains and what the quality string means.", "A record contains an identifier, nucleotide sequence, separator, and encoded per-base quality scores; the scores express uncertainty in base calls, not biological expression.", ["HTS-SPECS","FASTQC"], ["identifier|read name", "nucleotide sequence|base sequence", "quality score|phred"]),
        ("A student says a green FastQC summary proves the sample is biologically valid. Correct the statement.", "FastQC flags technical patterns relative to expectations; a pass is not proof of biological validity, and assay-specific expectations and metadata still require review.", ["FASTQC"], ["technical quality|quality control", "assay context|library type", "not proof|does not prove"]),
        ("Distinguish SAM, BAM, and CRAM in a way that would guide a new analyst choosing storage and exchange formats.", "SAM is textual alignment data, BAM is its binary equivalent, and CRAM is a reference-oriented compressed format; interoperability, reference identity, tooling, and archival needs matter.", ["HTS-SPECS"], ["SAM textual|SAM text", "BAM binary", "CRAM compressed|reference based"]),
        ("What is a VCF record intended to represent, and why must the header and reference build travel with the file?", "VCF represents variant sites and annotations/genotypes. Header definitions and the exact reference assembly are required to interpret coordinates, alleles, FILTER/INFO/FORMAT fields, and samples.", ["HTS-SPECS"], ["variant site|variant record", "reference assembly|genome build", "header definition|INFO FORMAT"]),
        ("Explain germline versus somatic variation and name the specimen comparison usually needed to distinguish them in cancer sequencing.", "Germline variants are inherited/present constitutionally; somatic variants arise in the tumor. A tumor-normal comparison helps distinguish them, subject to purity and assay limitations.", ["AMP-SOMATIC","ACMG-AMP"], ["germline inherited|constitutional", "somatic tumor|acquired", "matched normal|tumor normal"]),
        ("What is the difference between a gene-disease relationship and a variant classification?", "Gene-disease validity asks whether variation in a gene causes a defined disease; variant classification asks how a specific variant affects that relationship. Strong evidence for one does not automatically establish the other.", ["CLINGEN-GDV","ACMG-AMP"], ["gene disease validity|gene disease relationship", "specific variant|variant classification", "not automatically|separate"]),
        ("Name the five ACMG/AMP germline sequence-variant categories and explain why a VUS is not a positive result.", "The categories are pathogenic, likely pathogenic, uncertain significance, likely benign, and benign. A VUS lacks sufficient evidence and should not be treated as disease-causing.", ["ACMG-AMP"], ["pathogenic", "uncertain significance|VUS", "not actionable|not disease causing"]),
        ("A colleague treats biological and technical replicates as interchangeable. Explain the difference.", "Biological replicates sample independent biological units and support inference about biological variability; technical replicates assess measurement/process variability and are not independent biological evidence.", ["NIH-RIGOR"], ["independent biological|biological units", "measurement variability|technical variation", "not independent|pseudoreplication"]),
        ("What does normalization try to accomplish in RNA-seq, and what can it not repair?", "Normalization adjusts systematic scale/composition differences so counts are comparable under model assumptions. It cannot repair confounded design, mislabeled samples, severe degradation, or missing biology.", ["DESEQ2"], ["library size|composition", "comparable counts|systematic differences", "cannot repair|confounding"]),
        ("Why does DESeq2 model raw counts with a negative binomial distribution rather than run a t test on normalized counts?", "DESeq2 models count mean-variance behavior and biological dispersion with a negative binomial GLM; its inference and normalization are built for count data, unlike a simple t test.", ["DESEQ2"], ["negative binomial", "dispersion|mean variance", "count data|raw counts"]),
        ("What do sensitivity and specificity measure, and why are they insufficient without prevalence or predictive values for deployment?", "Sensitivity is the true-positive rate and specificity the true-negative rate. Predictive values and clinical consequences depend on prevalence and the intended population.", ["TRIPOD-AI","PROBAST-AI"], ["true positive|sensitivity", "true negative|specificity", "prevalence|predictive value"]),
        ("Distinguish discrimination from calibration in a clinical prediction model.", "Discrimination separates people with and without the outcome; calibration measures agreement between predicted probabilities and observed frequencies. A model can discriminate well yet be poorly calibrated.", ["TRIPOD-AI","PROBAST-AI"], ["separate|rank", "predicted probabilities|observed", "both|not same"]),
        ("What does FAIR mean for a biomedical dataset?", "FAIR means Findable, Accessible, Interoperable, and Reusable, supported by persistent identifiers, metadata, standard protocols/vocabularies, provenance, licensing, and community standards.", ["FAIR"], ["findable", "interoperable", "reusable"]),
        ("What is tumor purity, and how can low purity affect a somatic variant allele fraction?", "Tumor purity is the fraction of tumor cells/DNA in a specimen. Normal-cell admixture can dilute somatic alleles, lowering observed VAF and sensitivity; copy number and clonality also matter.", ["AMP-SOMATIC"], ["tumor fraction|tumor cellularity", "normal admixture|normal cells", "lower allele fraction|dilute"]),
        ("Why is a reference genome assembly identifier part of a reproducible variant result?", "Coordinates and reference alleles are assembly-specific. Recording the exact assembly and sequence identifiers prevents ambiguous or wrong locus interpretation.", ["HTS-SPECS","FAIR"], ["assembly specific|genome build", "coordinate", "reference allele|sequence identifier"]),
        ("Explain what joint genotyping adds after per-sample gVCF generation in a germline cohort.", "Joint genotyping evaluates sites coherently across samples, leveraging cohort-wide information for consistent genotypes and scalable incremental analysis; it is distinct from pooling raw reads.", ["GATK-BP"], ["cohort|multiple samples", "consistent genotype|joint analysis", "gVCF|genomic VCF"]),
        ("What is the clinical distinction between inherited cancer risk and a tumor biomarker used to select therapy?", "Inherited risk concerns constitutional variants and family implications; a tumor biomarker can be somatic or germline and may predict treatment response. Specimen, indication, evidence, and confirmatory testing must be clear.", ["NCI-BRCA","AMP-SOMATIC"], ["inherited|germline", "treatment response|therapy", "specimen|tumor"]),
        ("Why can BRCA1/2 dysfunction make a tumor sensitive to platinum or PARP inhibition?", "BRCA1/2 participate in homologous-recombination DNA repair. Loss can create repair deficiency and vulnerability to DNA damage or PARP inhibition, but indication and response are not guaranteed by a vague BRCA mention.", ["NCI-BRCA","NCI-OVARIAN"], ["homologous recombination|DNA repair", "PARP", "not guaranteed|indication"]),
        ("What is the difference between analytical validity, clinical validity, and clinical utility?", "Analytical validity is accurate/reliable measurement; clinical validity is the association with a phenotype or outcome; clinical utility is whether use improves decisions or outcomes in context.", ["CLINGEN-GDV","FDA-GMLP"], ["accurate measurement|analytical", "association|clinical validity", "improves outcome|clinical utility"]),
        ("A paper reports p=0.03. What can and cannot be concluded from that number alone?", "It indicates incompatibility with a specified null under assumptions; it does not give effect size, clinical importance, posterior truth, freedom from multiplicity, or study validity.", ["NIH-RIGOR"], ["null hypothesis|null", "effect size", "multiple testing|multiplicity"]),
    ]
}

LEVELS[2] = {
    "id": "L2_best_practice_reasoning", "category": "Best-practice workflow reasoning",
    "dimensions": ["best_practice_awareness", "workflow_planning", "bioinformatics_fundamentals"],
    "items": [
        ("Design the first-pass QC sequence for a new paired-end RNA-seq cohort before differential expression.", "Verify sample sheet and checksums, inspect raw-read QC and contamination, assess alignment/quantification metrics, sample identity and outliers, then model design and count distributions before inference.", ["FASTQC","DESEQ2","NIH-RIGOR"], ["metadata|sample sheet", "raw read QC|FastQC", "sample identity|outlier"]),
        ("FastQC shows adapter content near read ends. Decide whether and how to trim without creating an automatic rule.", "Confirm library design and read-through, quantify impact, trim known adapters with recorded parameters if warranted, rerun QC, and assess downstream alignment; do not trim solely because of a generic flag.", ["FASTQC"], ["library design|assay context", "known adapter|trim adapter", "rerun QC|post trim"]),
        ("You receive 40 tumor BAMs with no manifest. What must be reconstructed before variant analysis?", "Recover specimen/patient identity, tumor-normal pairing, consent/use constraints, reference and alignment pipeline versions, read groups, assay design, QC, and chain of custody; stop if identity cannot be established.", ["HTS-SPECS","FAIR","AMP-SOMATIC"], ["sample identity|patient identity", "reference|genome build", "provenance|pipeline version"]),
        ("Plan a germline cohort workflow that allows samples to arrive over six months without recalling every sample from raw reads.", "Process each sample to a gVCF under a locked workflow, version references and intervals, consolidate gVCFs, then joint genotype the cohort and preserve QC/provenance for incremental updates.", ["GATK-BP","FAIR"], ["gVCF", "joint genotype|joint calling", "version|provenance"]),
        ("An RNA-seq design has treatment perfectly confounded with sequencing batch. What analysis is defensible?", "The treatment effect is not identifiable separately from batch. Do not claim a treatment effect; redesign/collect bridging samples or report the confounding and limit conclusions.", ["DESEQ2","NIH-RIGOR"], ["confounded|not identifiable", "cannot separate|no treatment effect", "redesign|new samples"]),
        ("How would you construct a DESeq2 design for paired pre/post samples measured across batches?", "Use patient as a blocking factor and include batch if estimable, then test the condition coefficient; verify the design matrix is full rank and inspect interactions if scientifically justified.", ["DESEQ2"], ["patient|subject", "blocking|paired", "full rank|design matrix"]),
        ("A collaborator wants to filter RNA-seq genes by fold change before statistical testing. Explain a safer sequence.", "Use independent low-count filtering consistent with the method, fit the prespecified model, control false discovery rate, and report shrunken effect sizes/uncertainty; avoid outcome-driven fold-change preselection.", ["DESEQ2"], ["low count|independent filtering", "false discovery|FDR", "effect size|fold change shrink"]),
        ("What artifacts and records make a bioinformatics analysis rerunnable one year later?", "Versioned code/workflow, environment/container, immutable inputs/checksums, references, parameters, metadata, seeds, logs, outputs, and provenance with licenses/access rules.", ["FAIR","NIH-RIGOR"], ["versioned code|workflow", "container|environment", "checksum|provenance"]),
        ("How should duplicate reads be handled in germline DNA, tumor DNA, and RNA-seq rather than by one universal rule?", "Interpret duplicates by assay and library design; mark/handle PCR or optical duplicates in DNA as appropriate, consider UMIs, and avoid assuming RNA duplicates are artifacts because expression creates genuine duplication.", ["FASTQC","NIH-RIGOR"], ["assay specific|library design", "PCR duplicate|optical duplicate", "RNA expression|genuine duplication"]),
        ("Plan contamination checks for a human sequencing cohort.", "Use sequence-level screens plus sample-relatedness/sex/genotype concordance where allowed, compare expected metadata, inspect mixture estimates, document thresholds, and investigate rather than silently dropping samples.", ["FASTQC","NIH-RIGOR"], ["contamination screen|mixture", "genotype concordance|sample identity", "investigate|document threshold"]),
        ("How would you validate a VCF transformation that normalizes multiallelic records?", "Use a pinned specification/tool/reference, retain provenance, compare allele/genotype semantics before and after, test edge cases and round trips, validate headers, and quantify any intentional representation changes.", ["HTS-SPECS","FAIR"], ["specification|VCF", "genotype|allele", "edge case|round trip"]),
        ("Define an evidence workflow for classifying a rare germline missense variant.", "Confirm the call and transcript, establish gene-disease validity, collect population, segregation, functional and computational evidence, apply disease-specific ACMG/AMP criteria, resolve conflicts, and document dates/sources.", ["ACMG-AMP","CLINGEN-GDV"], ["population evidence|allele frequency", "segregation|functional", "ACMG|criteria"]),
        ("A pharmacogenomic genotype is available. What should happen before a prescribing recommendation is generated?", "Translate genotype to phenotype using the relevant current guideline, confirm allele definition and test limitations, map to the specific drug/context, grade the recommendation, and require clinician review.", ["CPIC"], ["genotype to phenotype|phenotype", "drug guideline|CPIC", "clinician review|clinical context"]),
        ("How should a somatic variant report separate evidence from recommendation?", "Report validated variant and assay limitations, tier evidence by tumor type/indication, distinguish diagnostic/prognostic/predictive claims, cite current evidence, and avoid turning a biological hypothesis into therapy advice.", ["AMP-SOMATIC"], ["assay limitation", "tier|clinical significance", "diagnostic prognostic predictive"]),
        ("Plan external validation for a clinical prediction model developed at one hospital.", "Freeze model and preprocessing, evaluate in a clinically relevant independent setting/time/population, preserve the intended-use cohort and outcome definition, report discrimination and calibration with uncertainty and subgroup performance.", ["TRIPOD-AI","PROBAST-AI"], ["freeze model|locked model", "independent|external", "calibration|discrimination"]),
        ("Why should train/test splitting occur at the patient rather than image, note, or specimen level?", "Patient-level splitting prevents correlated records from the same person leaking identity or outcome signals across sets and inflating performance.", ["PROBAST-AI","FDA-GMLP"], ["patient level", "leakage", "inflated performance|optimistic"]),
        ("Design subgroup performance reporting for a biomedical AI model without treating fairness as one number.", "Prespecify relevant groups, report sample sizes, uncertainty, discrimination/calibration and error consequences, examine intersectional and missing-data patterns, and avoid declaring equity from nonsignificant differences.", ["PROBAST-AI","FDA-TRANSPARENCY"], ["subgroup|group", "sample size|uncertainty", "calibration|error"]),
        ("A biomarker threshold was chosen after inspecting the outcome data. How should evaluation proceed?", "Treat threshold selection as model fitting, perform it only in development data/cross-validation, lock it, then evaluate on untouched data and disclose the optimization to avoid optimistic bias.", ["TRIPOD-AI","PROBAST-AI"], ["threshold selection|model fitting", "lock|prespecify", "untouched|independent test"]),
        ("What should a model card or deployment note communicate to a clinical user?", "Intended use and users, inputs/outputs, population and exclusions, performance and uncertainty, limitations/bias, human oversight, failure handling, update/version status, and monitoring.", ["FDA-TRANSPARENCY","FDA-GMLP"], ["intended use", "limitations|bias", "monitoring|human oversight"]),
        ("How do you choose between a simple and complex model for a small biomedical dataset?", "Base the choice on sample size, events, signal, intended use, validation and calibration—not novelty. Prefer the least complex model that meets prespecified performance and utility with robust validation.", ["PROBAST-AI","TRIPOD-AI"], ["sample size|events", "validation|calibration", "simple|complexity"]),
    ]
}

LEVELS[3] = {
    "id": "L3_real_world_scenarios", "category": "Real-world scientific problem solving",
    "dimensions": ["scientific_reasoning", "workflow_planning", "uncertainty_calibration"],
    "items": [
        ("Two analysts get different variant counts from the same FASTQs. Lead the discrepancy investigation.", "Freeze inputs/checksums, compare reference/build, tools, versions, parameters, intervals and filtering, reproduce minimal stages, classify representational versus biological differences, and document resolution.", ["HTS-SPECS","FAIR","NIH-RIGOR"], ["checksum|same input", "reference|version", "parameter|filter"]),
        ("A PCA plot separates RNA-seq samples by processing date, which overlaps partly with disease. What do you do next?", "Verify metadata and identity, quantify confounding, inspect QC and cell composition, model batch only if estimable, perform sensitivity analyses, and avoid claiming disease biology where batch cannot be separated.", ["DESEQ2","NIH-RIGOR"], ["metadata|sample identity", "confounding|batch", "sensitivity analysis|cannot separate"]),
        ("One sample has ten times fewer reads than its peers but clusters normally. Decide whether to exclude it.", "Do not exclude by a single threshold. Check cause, assay-specific power/coverage, mapping and complexity, influence on estimates, prespecified criteria, and sensitivity with/without the sample; document the decision.", ["FASTQC","NIH-RIGOR"], ["investigate cause|QC", "prespecified|exclusion criteria", "sensitivity|with and without"]),
        ("A tumor-only panel finds a pathogenic BRCA1 variant. Draft the interpretation boundary.", "It may be somatic or germline and must be interpreted in tumor/indication context. Do not infer inherited risk; recommend confirmatory germline evaluation/counseling when appropriate and state assay/VAF/purity limitations.", ["AMP-SOMATIC","NCI-BRCA","ACMG-AMP"], ["somatic or germline", "confirmatory germline|genetic counseling", "do not infer inherited"]),
        ("A model's AUROC is 0.91 internally and 0.68 at a second hospital. Frame the next investigation.", "Treat the external drop as evidence of limited transportability; compare case mix, acquisition, labels, missingness and calibration, audit leakage, quantify uncertainty/subgroups, and do not deploy before local validation or revision.", ["TRIPOD-AI","PROBAST-AI"], ["transportability|external", "case mix|dataset shift", "do not deploy|local validation"]),
        ("The label for mortality was extracted from notes written after the prediction time. Explain and repair the problem.", "This is temporal/target leakage. Rebuild features using only information available at the decision time, enforce timestamp cutoffs, repeat patient-level validation, and report the invalidated prior estimate.", ["PROBAST-AI","TRIPOD-AI"], ["temporal leakage|target leakage", "prediction time|timestamp", "repeat validation|invalidate"]),
        ("A pathway analysis is significant only after trying six gene-set databases and three ranking choices. How should it be reported?", "Disclose the analytic multiplicity and exploratory nature, control or contextualize false discovery, report all tried analyses or a multiverse/sensitivity view, and validate the selected signal independently.", ["NIH-RIGOR","FAIR"], ["multiplicity|multiple", "exploratory", "independent validation|sensitivity"]),
        ("A differential-expression hit has a tiny adjusted p value but a negligible fold change. Explain it to a biologist.", "Strong statistical evidence can coexist with a small effect, especially with high information. Discuss effect magnitude, uncertainty, biological relevance, assay artifacts and validation rather than equating significance with importance.", ["DESEQ2","NIH-RIGOR"], ["effect size|fold change", "statistical significance", "biological relevance|validation"]),
        ("A classifier fails mostly on samples from one sequencing instrument. What is your response plan?", "Stratify errors and QC by instrument, test whether instrument is a shortcut/confounder, reproduce preprocessing, collect balanced data, validate across instruments, and consider recalibration only after root-cause analysis.", ["FDA-GMLP","PROBAST-AI"], ["instrument|device", "confounder|shortcut", "validate across|balanced"]),
        ("A collaborator asks you to remove an outlier because it weakens the hypothesis. Respond as project analyst.", "Require a prespecified, measurement-based exclusion rationale independent of outcome; investigate identity/QC, retain an audit trail, show analyses with and without it, and refuse hypothesis-driven deletion.", ["NIH-RIGOR"], ["prespecified|exclusion criteria", "audit trail|document", "with and without|sensitivity"]),
        ("Half the cohort lacks a key laboratory predictor. Plan analysis rather than simply dropping those patients.", "Characterize missingness by outcome/site/time/group, assess plausible mechanisms, use appropriate imputation within resampling without leakage, include missingness sensitivity analyses, and report applicability limits.", ["TRIPOD-AI","PROBAST-AI"], ["missingness mechanism|missing data", "imputation within|resampling", "sensitivity|applicability"]),
        ("A rare-disease model has only 22 outcome events and 120 candidate features. Advise the team.", "The effective sample is too small for unconstrained feature search. Reduce/prespecify predictors, use penalization with nested validation, quantify optimism and uncertainty, and seek more data/external validation.", ["PROBAST-AI","TRIPOD-AI"], ["events|sample size", "reduce predictors|penalization", "optimism|external validation"]),
        ("A VCF annotation changed after a database update. How do you preserve interpretability of the earlier report?", "Retain original annotation database/version/date and evidence, distinguish reinterpretation from raw call changes, rerun under a documented policy, and issue a traceable amended result if clinically required.", ["AMP-SOMATIC","ACMG-AMP","FAIR"], ["version|date", "reinterpretation|reanalysis", "traceable|provenance"]),
        ("A patient-level model looks excellent using random cross-validation but poor using temporal validation. Which result matters and why?", "Temporal performance is more relevant to prospective use and reveals drift or leakage hidden by random folds. Investigate time-related changes and use the evaluation matching intended deployment.", ["TRIPOD-AI","PROBAST-AI"], ["temporal validation", "drift|time", "intended use|deployment"]),
        ("A clinical stakeholder asks for one accuracy number. Give a concise but responsible answer plan.", "Start with intended use and prevalence, then report confusion-matrix metrics, discrimination, calibration, uncertainty, subgroup performance and decision consequences at the operating threshold.", ["TRIPOD-AI","FDA-TRANSPARENCY"], ["intended use|prevalence", "calibration|discrimination", "subgroup|uncertainty"]),
        ("A multi-site study has site-specific outcome definitions. Can pooling fix it?", "No. Harmonize or explicitly model outcome definitions, quantify site heterogeneity and label reliability, consider site-stratified evaluation, and limit the target claim if a common outcome cannot be established.", ["TRIPOD-AI","PROBAST-AI"], ["harmonize|outcome definition", "site heterogeneity", "cannot|limit claim"]),
        ("You inherit an analysis notebook that runs only on the original laptop. Turn it into a reviewable workflow.", "Separate code/config/data, pin environment and references, add workflow orchestration and tests, capture seeds/logs/checksums, create a small reproducible example, and document access/provenance.", ["FAIR","NIH-RIGOR"], ["pin environment|container", "workflow|test", "seed|checksum"]),
        ("A model returns a treatment suggestion unsupported by the supplied tumor type. How should the system handle it?", "Block or flag the suggestion, require indication-specific evidence and current regulatory/guideline review, communicate uncertainty, route to a qualified clinician, and log the failure for monitoring.", ["AMP-SOMATIC","FDA-TRANSPARENCY"], ["indication specific|tumor type", "clinician review|qualified", "block|flag"]),
        ("A sample swaps sex chromosomes relative to recorded sex. What do you say and do?", "Treat it as an identity/QC alert, not a diagnosis or assumption about gender. Verify metadata, genotype concordance and technical explanations under privacy rules; quarantine affected results until resolved.", ["NIH-RIGOR","FDA-TRANSPARENCY"], ["identity|sample swap", "not diagnosis|gender", "verify metadata|quarantine"]),
        ("An external collaborator cannot access raw data. How can the analysis remain FAIR and auditable?", "FAIR does not mean unrestricted access. Provide rich metadata, identifiers, controlled-access procedures, code/workflows, synthetic/test data, provenance and result artifacts while honoring consent and governance.", ["FAIR"], ["not unrestricted|controlled access", "metadata|identifier", "code|provenance"]),
    ]
}
